definition.value: Any azaalkane in which two or more carbons in the chain are replaced by nitrogen.
A monovalent inorganic anion that consists of phosphoric acid in which one of the three OH groups has been deprotonated.
Guanosine substituted at the purine 8-position by a hydroxy group. It is used as a biomarker of oxidative DNA damage.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of adenosine 5'-monophosphate (AMP) obtained by selective protonation at position N1 on the purine moiety.
The S-enantiomer of adrenaline.
A galactopyranose having D-configuration.
A glucopyranose having D-configuration.
A D-glucoside that is derived by formal reaction of the primary hydroxy group of sphingosine at the anomeric position of  D-glucose.
The D-enantiomer of glucuronic acid.
A straight-chain alkane with 10 carbon atoms.
A hexose that has D-configuration at position 5.
A dihydroxyphenylacetic acid having the two hydroxy substituents located at the 3- and 4-positions. It is a metabolite of dopamine.
An optically active form of lactic acid having (R)-configuration.
An optically active form of lactic acid having (S)-configuration.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid containing fifteen-carbon atoms.
A D-glucopyranuronic acid in which the anomeric centre has alpha-configuration.
A L-galactopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric center.
A phosphate ion that is the conjugate base of dihydrogenphosphate.
A primary aliphatic amine that is butane substituted by an amino group at position 1.
A tetracosenoic acid having a cis-double bond at position 15.
A mucopolysaccharide consisting of repeating beta-(1->4)-linked L-iduronyl-(alpha1->3)-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine units.
A nucleoside 5'-monophosphate(2-) that results from the removal of two protons from the phosphate group of adenosine 5'-monophosphate (AMP).
A nucleoside 5'-diphosphate(3-) arising from deprotonation of all three diphosphate OH groups of adenosine 5'-diphosphate (ADP); major species present at pH 7.3.
N-Acetylneuraminic acid with beta configuration at the anomeric centre.
An amino aldehyde that is L-tyrosine in which the carboxy group has undergone formal redution to give the corrresponding aldehyde
A ubiquinone having a side chain of 10 isoprenoid units. In the naturally occurring isomer, all isoprenyl double bonds are in the E- configuration.
A nucleoside triphosphate(4-) obtained by global deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of UTP; major species present at pH 7.3.

In general, a mineral is a chemical substance that is normally crystalline formed and has been formed as a result of geological processes. The term also includes metamict substances (naturally occurring, formerly crystalline substances whose crystallinity has been destroyed by ionising radiation) and can include naturally occurring amorphous substances that have never been crystalline ('mineraloids') such as georgite and calciouranoite as well as substances formed by the action of geological processes on bigenic compounds ('biogenic minerals').
Any molecule that contains two amino-acid residues connected by peptide linkages.
A liquid that can dissolve other substances (solutes) without any change in their chemical composition.
